Linux man, 
"Man man" explains how man shows the manual for many things, not only programs, but also system calls, and many others, grouped in secctions
The section number is shown in the upper part of the page

ls(1)

this numbers correspond to: 
      1   Executable programs or shell commands
       2   System calls (functions provided by the kernel)
       3   Library calls (functions within program libraries)
       4   Special files (usually found in /dev)
       5   File formats and conventions eg /etc/passwd
       6   Games
       7   Miscellaneous (including macro packages and conventions), e.g. man(7), groff(7)
       8   System administration commands (usually only for root)
       9   Kernel routines [Non standard]

And by default man <page> shows the first page following the default section order "1 n l 8 3 2 3posix 3pm 3perl 5 4 9 6 7

To view a specific section:
"man 1 ls"

To view all sections under a name:
"whatis write" returns:
          write (1)            - send a message to another user
          write (2)            - write to a file descriptor
or approppos/ man -k do a regex search in names and descriptions
"apropos '^write' " returns:
          ...
          wall (1)             - write a message to users
          wodim (1)            - write data to optical disk media
          write (1)            - send a message to another user
          write (2)            - write to a file descriptor
          writev (2)           - read or write data into multiple buffers
          XvPutStill (3)       - write a single frame of video to a drawable
          ...


